    <h2 style="margin-top: 0;">CHAPTER 5 - Query Engine vs Retriever (Critical Distinction)</h2>

    <h3>What's the Confusion?</h3>
    <p>Most of the devs think:</p>
    <pre><code class="language-text">Query → Index → Answer</code></pre>
    <div class="mistake-box">
        <strong>Wrong!!</strong>
    </div>

    <h3>Core Insight</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Retriever</strong> finds relevant data</li>
        <li><strong>Query Engine</strong> orchestrates the full answer generation</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Actual Model</h3>
    <pre><code class="language-text">User Query
   ↓
Retriever → returns nodes (raw data)
   ↓
Query Engine → uses LLM to synthesize answer</code></pre>

    <h3>1. Retriever (Data Fetching Layer)</h3>
    <h4>What it does</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>It takes the user query</li>
        <li>And retrieves relevant nodes from the index.</li>
        <li>Returns them</li>
    </ul>
    <p>That's it. No LLM involved. No answer generation. Just data fetching.</p>

    <h4>Example:</h4>
    <pre><code class="language-python">retriever = index.as_retriever(similarity_top_k=3)

nodes = retriever.retrieve("What has Sasidhar built?")

for node in nodes:
    print(node.text)</code></pre>

    <h4>Output:</h4>
    <pre><code class="language-text">"Sasidhar built an ATS system..."
"He developed a backend AI system..."</code></pre>

