    <h3>Troubleshooting Common Query Engine Issues</h3>

    <p><strong>1. "Answer is wrong but nodes are correct"</strong><br>
        This means the retriever is working but the LLM is not synthesizing the answer correctly.<br>
        <strong>Fix:</strong>
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>better prompt engineering</li>
        <li>use a more powerful LLM</li>
        <li>response mode (we'll learn in next modules)</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>2. Retriever returns irrelevant nodes</strong><br>
        Cause:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>embeddings</li>
        <li>chunking</li>
        <li>top_k too small</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Fix:</strong></p>
    <ul>
        <li>improve chunking</li>
        <li>use better embedding model</li>
        <li>increase <code>similarity_top_k</code> to fetch more nodes</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>3. Query engine hides too much</strong><br>
        Yes, query engines are great for simplicity, but they can hide the retrieval process, making it harder to debug
        when things go wrong.</p>
    <p><strong>For Production:</strong></p>
    <ul>
        <li>we often bypass it and build custom pipelines for better control and observability.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Advanced Insight</h3>
    <pre><code class="language-text">Retriever = Recall problem
Query Engine = Reasoning problem</code></pre>

    <p><strong>We optimize them differently:</strong></p>
    <ul>
        <li>For <strong>retriever</strong> → we optimize chunking, embeddings, index structure.</li>
        <li>For <strong>query engine</strong> → we optimize prompts, LLM choice, response synthesis.</li>
    </ul>

